nd":"Grove, Nottinghamshire, England"},"nl":{"1175–9 July 1241":"1175–9 juli 1241","1161–1241":"1161–1241","1170–Male":"1170–Overleden","1175–1241":"1175–1241","1179–1195":"1179–1195","–1247":"–1247","–1304":"–1304","1132–Male":"1132–Overleden","1132–1183":"1132–1183","3 Nov 1183":"3 november 1183","1132":"1132","1175":"1175","1241":"1241","1195":"1195","1183":"1183","1161":"1161","1170":"1170","1304":"1304","1247":"1247","1179":"1179","1199":"1199","9 July 1241":"9 juli 1241","Caen, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, France":"Caen, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, Frankrijk","Walsall, Staffordshire, England":"Walsall, Staffordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Grove, Nottinghamshire, England":"Grove, Nottinghamshire, England"},"en":{"1175–9 July 1241":"1175–9 July 1241","1161–1241":"1161–1241","1170–Male":"1170–Deceased","1175–1241":"1175–1241","1179–1195":"1179–1195","–1247":"–1247","–1304":"–1304","1132–Male":"1132–Deceased","1132–1183":"1132–1183","3 Nov 1183":"3 November 1183","1132":"1132","1175":"1175","1241":"1241","1195":"1195","1183":"1183","1161":"1161","1170":"1170","1304":"1304","1247":"1247","1179":"1179","1199":"1199","9 July 1241":"9 July 1241","Caen, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, France":"Caen, Calvados, Lower Normandy, France","Walsall, Staffordshire, England":"Walsall, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Grove, Nottinghamshire, England":"Grove, Nottinghamshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ruffus","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from a place in Morayshire called Duffus.","English: nickname or topographic name from Middle English <i>douvehous</i>, <i>duffous</i> ‘dovecote’, for someone who lived by or worked in a dovehouse. It is possible that the English form of this name died out in or after the medieval period.","Possibly also an Americanized form of Dutch <b>Duffhues</b> or <b>Duifhuis</b>: topographic or habitational name referring to a house or a farm distinguished by a dovecot (compare 2 above) and named so."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Ruffus III was born in 1175, in Walsall, West Midlands, England, United Kingdom, his father, William Ruffus, was 43 and his mother, Matilda de le Bonnaire, was 43. He married Isabel d'Arques in 1199, in Grove, Nottinghamshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. He died on 9 July 1241, in Walsall, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 66."},"et":{"1175–9 July 1241":"1175–9. juuli 1241","1161–1241":"1161–1241","1170–Male":"1170–Surnud","1175–1241":"1175–1241","1179–1195":"1179–1195","–1247":"–1247","–1304":"–1304","1132–Male":"1132–Surnud","1132–1183":"1132–1183","3 Nov 1183":"3. november 1183","1132":"1132","1175":"1175","1241":"1241","1195":"1195","1183":"1183","1161":"1161","1170":"1170","1304":"1304","1247":"1247","1179":"1179","1199":"1199","9 July 1241":"9. juuli 1241","Caen, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, France":"Caen, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Walsall, Staffordshire, England":"Walsall, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Grove, Nottinghamshire, England":"Grove, Nottinghamshire, England"},"fi":{"1175–9 July 1241":"1175–9. heinäkuuta 1241",